The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Hapur (Uttar Pradesh) Jan. 21 (PTI): A letter allegedly written by Pakistan-based terror group Jaish-e-Mohammed has threatened to blow up a dozen railway stations, including those in Delhi, Meerut and Ghaziabad, on Republic Day. Movie halls, the Delhi zoo and top politicians are on the threat list.           
	Hapur station master S.S. Rana received the letter late this evening. Security has been tightened, officials said.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): Actor Sanjay Dutt has said his late father Sunil Dutt, a Congress leader, might have been upset over his joining the Samajwadi Party. But he said he would have been able to convince his father as both parties have similar views on secularism.                   
	 Chandigarh (PTI): The constituent states of the National Capital Region  Haryana, Delhi, Rajasthan and Uttar Pradesh  have reached a common transport agreement to facilitate unrestricted and seamless movement of inter-state traffic and control their operations. This will facilitate movement of taxis and autorickshaws within the NCR.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The health ministry has directed officials to look into reports of cruelty against animals used for research at the AIIMS. Anbumani Ramadosss directive came on a petition from former health minister Shatrughan Sinha on behalf of PETA.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Lok Sabha speaker Somnath Chatterjee said judges of higher courts should be subjected to accountability for declaration of assets and public interest litigation cases. He called the Indian judiciary unique because here judges appoint themselves. A commission could be formed for consultation on the appointment of judges, he said.                  
	 Srinagar (PTI): Nearly eight lakh migratory birds have visited the Kashmir valley, the highest ever recorded. This is in contrast to 25,000 birds in 1992. Authorities were concerned over the danger of bird flu, but no such case has been found.                                                                                                                           
